- **Item:** Governance requirements in enterprise RFPs

  - **Trigger:** explicit governance checklists or audit requirements

  - **Why it matters:** signals transition from preference to requirement

  - **Current status:** monitor

- **Item:** Pricing standardization for AI-assisted workflows

  - **Trigger:** repeatable pricing models or benchmarks

  - **Why it matters:** impacts margins and buyer expectations

  - **Current status:** monitor

- **Item:** Model control (BYOM/BYC) becoming standard

  - **Trigger:** widespread vendor support and buyer demand

  - **Why it matters:** shifts control layer in the stack

  - **Current status:** monitor

- **Item:** Evidence of workflow consolidation in litigation/eDiscovery

  - **Trigger:** buyer-side vendor consolidation or platform adoption

  - **Why it matters:** reshapes competitive landscape

  - **Current status:** monitor

***


## **8. Confidence Notes**

- **Governance as a core driver:** high confidence, strong multi-source alignment

- **Data/retrieval as moat:** high confidence, consistent vendor and product signals

- **Pricing normalization:** moderate confidence, still early

- **Shared client intelligence:** lower confidence, limited direct evidence

***


## **9. What Would Change Our Mind**

- **Governed AI as a requirement:** → If buyers consistently prioritize speed/capability over governance

- **Data + retrieval as moat:** → If foundation model improvements erase differentiation

- **Deployment architecture importance:** → If buyers accept standardized vendor-managed environments at scale

- **Workflow orchestration trend:** → If adoption remains fragmented and tool-centric 

